## What Is a Pink Cushion Cut Diamond?

A pink cushion cut diamond is a cushion-shaped diamond graded by GIA (or IGI for lab) as having a pink primary or secondary hue. The cushion cut — with its rounded corners and large open facets — is the preferred shape for fancy color diamonds precisely because it retains and amplifies body color better than brilliant-cut shapes.

Pink diamonds get their color from a structural phenomenon, not from chemical inclusions. During formation deep in the earth, extreme pressure causes lattice deformation in the carbon crystal structure. This deformation selectively absorbs green light — and the reflected light reads as pink to the human eye. This is why the Argyle mine in Western Australia, sitting on an ancient volcanic formation with unusually high-pressure geology, produced over 90% of the world's pink diamonds.

Cushion cut is not an accident of preference. It is a deliberate optical choice for pink. Read on for why.

