## The Colour Cut Advantage

Cushion cut is not the most popular shape for pink diamonds by accident. It is the deliberate choice of every serious pink diamond buyer in the world — and there's an optical reason for it.

The Colour Cut Advantage works like this: a cushion modified cut has larger, chunkier facets than a round brilliant. Where a round brilliant's 57 precisely angled facets disperse and break up light, the cushion's facets act as pools — holding and deepening body color instead of scattering it. For color diamonds where saturation is everything, this matters enormously.

In practical terms: a GIA Fancy Brownish Pink cushion will show visibly more pink saturation than the same stone cut round. The cushion's open table and wider facet structure allows the stone's bodycolor to come through face-up. This is why the world's most famous pink diamonds — including the 59.60ct Pink Star and the Graff Pink — are cushion cuts. It's not aesthetics. It's physics.

For pink specifically, the Colour Cut Advantage also works with the stone's depth. Pink color in diamonds comes from structural deformation of the carbon lattice, not from surface coating. A deeper cushion cut with a higher pavilion gives the light more travel distance through the colored crystal — increasing perceived saturation at the face-up position. This is why cushion modified cuts (which tend to be slightly deeper than standard cushions) are so common in the GIA pink diamond dataset.

When buying a pink cushion cut, look for a higher depth percentage (63–66%) compared to a white cushion where you'd cap at 62.3%. In color diamonds, depth adds saturation, not darkness.

