## Argyle Pink Cushion Cut Diamond — The Mine That Changed Everything

The Argyle diamond mine in Western Australia operated from 1983 to 2020. In those 37 years, it produced over 90% of the world's pink diamonds. Then it closed permanently.

Argyle graded its pink diamonds on a proprietary system using numbers and letters:
- **1PP, 2PP** = Fancy Vivid Purplish Pink (the rarest, most expensive)
- **1P, 2P, 3P** = descending pink intensity
- **PR** = Pink Rose (lighter pink with rose undertones)
- **PC** = Pink Champagne (pinkish-brown)

The finest Argyle pinks — grades 1PP through 3PP — were sold through annual invitation-only tenders. Collectors from around the world bid. The public couldn't participate. Stones under 1ct sold for hundreds of thousands per carat.

Since the 2020 closure, existing Argyle-certified stones have become collector's items in their own right. Prices for certified Argyle pinks rose 20–40% after the closure was announced. If you encounter an Argyle-certified pink cushion cut diamond through a dealer, expect to pay a significant premium above comparable GIA-graded stones — the Argyle certificate itself is part of the value now.

What you cannot do: buy a new Argyle pink diamond anywhere. The mine is exhausted. What circulates in the market is existing inventory, and it is declining every year as more pieces move into private collections where they stay.

For buyers who want an Argyle-grade look without Argyle-grade prices: this is exactly why The Lab Sovereign matters.

---

## The Lab Sovereign

Natural fancy pink cushion cut diamonds with pure "Fancy Pink", "Fancy Intense Pink", or "Fancy Vivid Pink" grading are not retail purchases. They are collectibles, investment vehicles, and auction trophies. A 1ct Fancy Intense Pink at [$400,060](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-23341915?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is not bought by someone planning a proposal. It is bought by a collector who understands the global rarity of the grade.

Lab-grown technology has changed this completely. Pink color in lab diamonds is achieved through HPHT post-growth treatment that introduces the same nitrogen/structural modification responsible for natural pink. The result is a stone with the same optical properties, the same face-up color, and a fraction of the price — without any mine, any Argyle tender, any auction.

The Lab Sovereign is the reality that lab-grown pink cushion has become the de facto option for every buyer below the $100,000 threshold. Lab pink has not just competed with natural pink — it has taken over the retail category entirely. When someone buys a pink cushion cut engagement ring today, they are almost certainly buying lab. The exceptions are collectors, investors, and the ultra-wealthy who buy natural for provenance, not appearance.

This is not a compromise. A [5ct IGI Fancy Vivid Pink VS1 lab cushion at $3,045](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-29194960?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) has a stronger color grade than any natural stone in our Blue Nile dataset. No natural Fancy Vivid Pink cushion exists at any price in that dataset. The lab stone is the sovereign of its own category now.

