## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is a pink cushion cut diamond?
A pink cushion cut diamond is a cushion-shaped diamond graded by GIA or IGI as having a pink primary hue. Pink color in natural diamonds comes from structural deformation of the carbon crystal lattice during formation — not from chemical inclusions. Lab-grown pink diamonds achieve the same effect through HPHT post-growth treatment. Cushion cut is preferred for pink diamonds because its larger facets pool and amplify body color better than any other shape.

### How much does a pink cushion cut diamond cost?
Natural: from [$9,488 for a 1ct GIA Fancy Brownish Pink SI2](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-28204124?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) to [$979,347 for a 1.02ct GIA Fancy Intense Purplish Pink](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-21749730?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Lab-grown: from [$3,045 for a 5ct IGI Fancy Vivid Pink VS1](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-29194960?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Natural price is driven by GIA color grade and modifier.

### What is a fancy pink cushion cut diamond?
"Fancy" is a GIA intensity grade — it sits above Fancy Light and below Fancy Intense in the pink color hierarchy. A GIA Fancy Pink cushion with no brown modifier starts around $38,000 for 1ct ([$38,006 Fancy Brown Pink VS2](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-20891251?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)) and climbs steeply as modifiers clear and intensity rises.

### What is a light pink cushion cut diamond?
"Light pink" is not an official GIA grade — buyers using this term typically want a GIA Fancy Light Pink or Light Pink grade, which is softer and more blush-toned than Fancy Pink. These grades exist in natural diamonds but are still expensive ($2,000–$10,000/ct) due to rarity. Lab-grown IGI "Fancy Light Pink" cushion cuts are available at lower prices and are worth searching on Blue Nile if you want a delicate blush tone.

### Are lab grown pink cushion cut diamonds real diamonds?
Yes. Lab-grown pink diamonds are chemically identical to natural diamonds — pure carbon in cubic crystal structure. IGI certifies their pink color grade using the same criteria as GIA uses for natural stones. The difference is origin: natural pink formed over billions of years under pressure; lab pink grew in a controlled environment in weeks. No jeweler or gemologist can distinguish them without specialized spectroscopy.

### What is an Argyle pink cushion cut diamond?
An Argyle pink diamond is a pink diamond certified by the Argyle mine in Western Australia, which produced 90% of the world's pink diamonds before closing in 2020. Argyle graded pinks on a proprietary scale (1PP through 9PC). The finest grades (1PP, 2PP) were sold through invitation-only annual tenders at extraordinary prices. Since the closure, certified Argyle pink cushion cuts trade as collectibles at premiums above comparable GIA stones. There is no new Argyle supply.

### Why are natural pink cushion cut diamonds so expensive?
Three reasons: rarity of pink color in diamonds (less than 0.01% of mined diamonds show any pink); closure of the Argyle mine in 2020 (which produced 90% of supply); and non-linear price escalation as color intensity increases. A 1ct natural Fancy Intense Pink is worth more than a 1ct natural Fancy Brown Pink, and neither can be compared to white diamond pricing of any kind.

### What is the difference between Fancy Brown Pink and Fancy Brownish Pink?
In GIA grading, when brown is listed first ("Fancy Brown Pink"), brown is the secondary hue — it modifies the primary pink. When brown is listed as an adjective ("Fancy Brownish Pink"), brown is a lesser component of the pink hue. In practice, "Fancy Brownish Pink" reads as pinker than "Fancy Brown Pink" to most eyes — which partly explains why the [1.02ct Fancy Brownish Pink at $9,488](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-28204124?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is cheaper than many "Fancy Brown Pink" stones — the market prices the primary hue order differently.

### What color intensity should I buy for a pink cushion cut diamond?
For lab-grown: Fancy Vivid Pink is available and affordable — the [5ct IGI FVP VS1 at $3,045](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-29194960?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is excellent. For natural: buy the highest modifier-free grade your budget allows. Fancy Brown Pink at $38,000/ct gives you a genuinely pink stone. Fancy Intense Pink starts at $339,000/ct and is collector territory.

### What setting is best for a pink cushion cut engagement ring?
Rose gold is the best setting for pink cushion cuts — the warm metal amplifies body color and creates a cohesive look. Platinum works with rose gold prongs if you prefer a bright shank. Avoid yellow gold (pulls pink toward orange-brown) and white gold halo settings that contrast too harshly with the stone's color. See our [cushion cut diamond guide](/cushion-cut-diamond) for detailed setting options.

### Is a pink cushion cut diamond good for everyday wear?
Yes — diamond is the hardest natural material (Mohs 10) and the cushion's rounded corners make it more chip-resistant than pointed cuts like princess or pear. The concerns for everyday wear are: setting security (use 4–6 prongs), and prong inspection annually for stones above 3ct. Lab-grown pink cushion cuts at 5–7ct in a secure bezel or prong setting are perfectly suited to daily wear.

### Why do lab pink diamonds come in such large sizes (5–7ct) at low prices?
Lab pink diamonds are produced through HPHT post-growth color treatment — a process that can be applied to large CVD-grown crystals without the geological constraints that make large natural pinks so rare. Growing a 7ct lab pink diamond is not materially harder than growing a 2ct one. This is why the [7ct IGI FVP VS1 costs $3,742](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-28760623?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — a price impossible for any natural pink stone at any carat weight.

### Where is the best place to buy a pink cushion cut diamond?
[Blue Nile](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamonds?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the strongest retail source for both natural and lab-grown pink cushion cuts — they have the largest online inventory of GIA and IGI certified colored diamonds with HD video for every stone. For certified Argyle pink diamonds, specialist dealers and auction houses (Christie's, Sotheby's) are the source — Argyle stones are rarely found on standard retail platforms.

### What is the Colour Cut Advantage for pink diamonds?
The Colour Cut Advantage is the optical phenomenon where cushion cut diamonds show stronger body color than round brilliant cuts at the same GIA grade. The cushion's larger, chunkier facets pool color instead of dispersing it. For pink diamonds — where saturation is everything — this means a pink cushion reads as visibly more saturated than a pink round at the same grade. This is why virtually all famous pink diamonds are cushion cuts.

### Lab pink vs natural pink: which should I buy?
If your budget is under $50,000: lab pink, with no hesitation. A [6ct lab FVP at $3,500](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/pink-25619658?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) has more color, more face-up impact, and a higher IGI grade than a 1ct natural Fancy Brown Pink at $38,000. If provenance, rarity, and resale value are your priorities — and budget is not the constraint — natural pink with GIA certification and no brown modifier is the choice. There is no middle ground: the two products serve different buyers entirely.
